    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"confidentiality period\" is simply the time window during which you are legally bound to keep secrets, while a \"survival clause\" is the legal mechanism that ensures those specific obligations (like confidentiality) survive the termination of the entire agreement. Think of it this way: the confidentiality period is the duration of the secret's life, but the survival clause is the contract's way of saying, \"Even if we break up, the secret stays buried.\"\n\nIt's a bit like a goblin's hoard; the goblin might be gone (the contract ends), but the gold (the confidential information) remains locked away because the goblin's rules (the survival clause) say it must stay hidden forever, regardless of whether the goblin is still there to guard it.\n\nIn a standard contract, you usually see the confidentiality period defined as a specific number of years after the deal ends, whereas the survival clause is a broader provision that lists which sections of the contract—like non-competes, indemnity, and yes, confidentiality—continue to apply post-termination. If you miss the survival clause, you might accidentally think the goblin is gone and start stealing the gold, only to find out the goblin's",
      "source": "target",
