    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely! Vague clauses are like a goblin hiding a treasure map inside a hollow log; you can't tell if the map is real or just wood until you try to dig, and by then, you might have lost your hand. In contract law, ambiguity is often interpreted against the drafter, but if the drafter is a slick lawyer (or a very cunning goblin), they might use vague language to trap you into a liability you never intended to accept.\n\nTo spot a clause trying to hide something, look for \"catch-all\" phrases like \"any and all losses,\" \"consequential damages,\" or \"indemnify against any claim,\" without defining what constitutes a \"claim.\" A good goblin would never say, \"I promise to pay for anything that happens,\" because that includes the goblin's own stupidity. Similarly, a vague indemnity clause might not specify that it only covers *your* negligence, leaving you on the hook for the client's gross negligence or even their own criminal acts.\n\nIf a clause doesn't explicitly state the time limit for reporting a claim, it's a red flag. It's like a goblin saying, \"If you find my gold, you must tell me immediately",
